msItem.title: Do bheirim barr búadha is áigh
msItem.incipit: Do bheirim barr búadha is áigh
msItem.explicit: ... o inber go bruach banna, futh no.

titleStmt.title: Do bheirim barr búadha is áigh

note.p: For this to conform to the metre the "a" before raiter should be omitted.
Lines 4c and 4d are manifestly corrupt: taineamh and tartha should rhyme with bathaidh and ainm.

Black (0120694) created a slip with the headword slabhra for this point, giving the quotation is ríoghsh[labhra]. As the MS is damaged at this point, his reading is also conjectural and the present editor thinks Professor William Gillies' suggestion of "ríoghdhamhna" would fit better in this context.

The letter preceding the d is strange and I am not quite sure what to make of it. It appears to have iniditally been a character, now illegible, which was subsequently changed. The 'corrected' reading may be intended to be 'ui'

Possibly corrupt. As ceadal and eagartha must rhyme, and of the two eagartha makes more sense. Thus, either ceadala has a short vowel, which we would not usually expect in bardic poetry, or we should have another word here for the rhyme to work. If we read ceadala with a short vowel, Black has suggested the sense "subject of song for the land of A[lba]."
Black (0121092) created a slip for this point of the MS with the headword tairmeasgadh but no dictionary slip. There is no further information given in this slip.
The lenition marker is placed over the final t in this word but has been transcribed as after the c to render the ending -cht.

Black (0130069) notes the headword here as tath. This is what it seems like is in the MS but if one looks closely there appears to be a faint superscript i over the second t, thus indicating that the headword would be tríath.

note.p: Black supplies the -in in the HDSG slip for "gath": (0002485).
Black supplies -in here in the quotation on the slip for dearbh (0060990).
Black (0110626) takes this as a form of ScG. oirthir whereas in this edition it is understood to be a form of the Early Gaelic airer.

While the most obvious meaning for this would be fruit, mast, or similar, the present editor cannot find such a word with similar spelling and meaning in eDIL, Dwelly or Ó Domhnaill. Perhaps the meaning is a back formation from búasach meaning wealthy but to postulate such a backformation it would likely have been understood to mean wealthy in more general agricultural terms or wealthy generally.
